Architecture plan for issues #1-#31

Module structure and file organization
- Use a full-stack web app with a dedicated frontend and backend laid out under top-level app directories, plus shared packages for cross-cutting contracts.
- Frontend: route-based pages for auth, organizer dashboard, event feed, event detail, event forms, profile, invite/RSVP flows, and reusable photo-forward UI components. Keep design tokens, layout shell, form controls, empty states, and upload widgets in a shared UI area.
- Backend: API modules grouped by domain: auth, users, events, invitations, RSVPs, comments, activity, uploads, mail, scheduler, and health/config. Keep route handlers thin and move business logic into services.
- Shared types: define request/response DTOs, enum values, validation schemas, and public model projections in one shared layer consumed by frontend and backend where the selected stack supports it. Keep database-only fields out of public types.
- Database: migrations are the source of truth. Model users first, then events, invitations/RSVPs, comments/activity history, and attachment metadata. Include timestamps, ownership fields, and indexes for organizer dashboards, event feeds, invite lookups, and reminder jobs.
- Storage: abstract uploads behind an attachment service so profile photos, event cover photos, and event PDFs share validation, metadata persistence, and provider-specific implementation details.
- Email: centralize transactional templates and delivery behind a mail service used by verification, password reset, invitations, RSVP confirmations, and reminders.
- Configuration: load environment variables through one typed config module. Include database URL, auth/session secrets, OAuth credentials, mail provider settings, upload storage settings, public origin/CORS configuration, and scheduler controls.

Issue dependency map
- #1 is the foundation for project structure, scripts, local development, and baseline CI assumptions.
- #2 depends on #1 and enables all persistence-backed features.
- #3 should land immediately after #1/#2 so later issues use typed configuration instead of ad hoc environment reads.
- #4 can start after #1 and should define the visual shell, tokens, page layout, and reusable components used by all frontend issues.
- #5-#12 form the auth/user track: user model, email/password auth, Google sign-in, persistent sessions, auth pages, email verification, password reset, and profile photo upload.
- #13-#18 form the event core track: event model, CRUD API, cover uploads, create/edit form, organizer dashboard, and event detail page.
- #19-#22 add collaboration and messaging: invitation/RSVP models, invite flow, RSVP endpoint/UI, and transactional emails.
- #23-#26 add engagement surfaces: comments, activity history, activity view, and photo-forward event feed.
- #27 builds on upload infrastructure and event ownership rules to add PDF attachments.
- #28 depends on events, RSVPs/invitations, email, and scheduler configuration.
- #29 should exercise the core happy paths across auth, event creation, invitations, RSVPs, comments, uploads, and reminders where practical.
- #30 should review every user-facing surface for validation, authorization failures, empty states, loading states, and recoverable errors.
- #31 should finalize deployment configuration, production environment documentation, proxy-aware origin handling, build commands, migrations, and operational checks.

Key design decisions
- Treat authentication and authorization as backend concerns first. Frontend route guards improve UX, but every protected API route must verify the session and ownership/membership rules.
- Use server-generated IDs and database constraints for integrity. Prefer explicit join/relationship tables for invitations, RSVPs, comments, activity, and attachments.
- Store uploaded file metadata in the database and binary data in the configured storage provider or local development storage abstraction.
- Make event visibility explicit: organizer-owned dashboard data is separate from member/invitee feed data.
- Normalize activity history as append-only events emitted by domain services when meaningful actions occur.
- Use idempotent scheduled reminder jobs keyed by event and recipient so retries do not duplicate emails.
- Respect reverse proxy headers in production. Public origin checks must use forwarded host/proto or the platform-provided allowed origin instead of raw Host.
- Keep implementation slices issue-sized: each issue should include focused tests for the new behavior and avoid broad rewrites outside its domain.
